<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="xp-extreme-programming">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>software-developer</domain>
    <summary>Agile methodology: 12 engineering practices, TDD, continuous integration, pair programming, simple design. For solo+AI: Claude as pair, TDD mandatory.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>xp</tag>
      <tag>tdd</tag>
      <tag>agile</tag>
      <tag>continuous-integration</tag>
      <tag>quality</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Extreme Programming (XP)</title>
    <summary>An agile methodology built on 12 engineering practices taken to their logical extreme: TDD (test everything), continuous integration (integrate many times daily), pair programming (review all code), simple design (fewest elements that pass), and collective ownership (anyone changes anything). For solo + AI dev, Claude acts as the pair partner and TDD is non-negotiable.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Teams adopting Scrum without engineering practices get process overhead without quality payoff. XP's practices are mutually reinforcing: TDD makes refactoring safe; refactoring keeps simple design; simple design enables collective ownership; collective ownership requires coding standards; standards are enforced by pre-commit and CI. Kent Beck's four rules of simple design are the concrete, testable definition of "clean code".</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Small teams (2-12) with rapidly changing requirements and direct customer access.</item>
        <item>Greenfield projects where TDD, CI, and pair programming can be established from day one.</item>
        <item>Recovering a brownfield codebase where quality has rotted — XP's practices are a culture reset.</item>
        <item>Solo + AI dev: most XP practices map cleanly onto a human-in-loop with Claude as the pair.</item>
        <item>Teams adopting agile but failing on engineering excellence (Scrum-without-XP).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Compliance-heavy / regulated work where every change needs upfront sign-off — "embrace change" clashes.</item>
        <item>Distributed teams with poor async culture and no shared timezone — pair programming falls apart.</item>
        <item>Outsourced arrangements where the customer is unreachable.</item>
        <item>Hardware / firmware where test-refactor cycle is dominated by hardware-in-loop.</item>
        <item>Research / exploratory ML where most code is thrown away — TDD overhead exceeds value.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="kent-becks-four-rules-of-simple-design">
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply Kent Beck's four rules in strict priority order: (1) passes all tests, (2) reveals intention, (3) no duplication, (4) fewest elements. A design that passes tests but is unreadable is better than one that is readable but fails tests; a design with duplication that passes tests is better than no-duplication code that does not.</statement>
        <rationale>The priority order resolves conflicts. Agents frequently violate rule 4 (fewest elements) by adding interfaces, strategies, and factories preemptively. The rule is the concrete, testable definition of over-engineering.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Rule 1: Passes all tests — correctness is the non-negotiable baseline.</item>
        <item>Rule 2: Reveals intention — names, structure, and comments communicate purpose without ambiguity.</item>
        <item>Rule 3: No duplication (DRY) — every piece of knowledge has one authoritative location.</item>
        <item>Rule 4: Fewest elements — no classes, methods, or interfaces that are not currently needed (YAGNI).</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="12-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Planning Game: customer prioritizes stories, team estimates; stories > 13 points are split.</item>
        <item>Small Releases: internal every iteration (1-2 weeks), external monthly or more frequently.</item>
        <item>Metaphor: shared vocabulary for the system domain; prevents naming drift.</item>
        <item>Simple Design: rules 1-4 above applied continuously, not just at start.</item>
        <item>TDD: failing test before production code, always. Non-negotiable.</item>
        <item>Refactoring: continuous design improvement in dedicated commits separate from feature changes.</item>
        <item>Pair Programming: two developers, one computer. For solo+AI: Claude as pair partner.</item>
        <item>Collective Ownership: any developer can change any code; requires strong standards + tests.</item>
        <item>Continuous Integration: integrate and run full test suite multiple times daily.</item>
        <item>Sustainable Pace: 40-hour weeks; tired developers make mistakes that cost more than the hours saved.</item>
        <item>On-site Customer: real decision-maker available for questions; PMs as proxies are acceptable.</item>
        <item>Coding Standards: consistent style across all code; enforced by pre-commit hooks.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="solo-and-ai-applicability">
      <list>
        <item>TDD — essential; run with Claude as the pair that writes failing tests first.</item>
        <item>Simple Design — essential; use rule 4 to reject agent-generated abstractions without 2+ concrete uses.</item>
        <item>Small Releases — essential; CI/CD automates the release gate.</item>
        <item>Continuous Integration — essential; GitHub Actions / GitLab CI is the substrate.</item>
        <item>Refactoring — essential; always in a separate commit from the feature change.</item>
        <item>Pair Programming — adapted; Claude drives the coding, human navigates and reviews.</item>
        <item>On-site Customer — adapted; async feedback via issue comments or recorded demos.</item>
        <item>Collective Ownership — not applicable solo; but use it to resist siloing knowledge in one module.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="red-green-refactor-loop">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write the failing test before writing any production code. Never write production code to pass a test that does not yet exist. Each red-green-refactor cycle produces three commits: (1) failing test, (2) minimum code to pass, (3) refactor.</statement>
        <rationale>Tests written after the fact verify the implementation that already exists, not the behavior that was intended. Pre-written tests catch intent drift immediately and make the refactor step verifiable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Refactor in a separate commit from feature changes. The refactor commit changes structure without changing behavior; the test suite must remain green before and after.</statement>
        <rationale>Combining refactor and feature in one commit makes the diff unreadable for review. Reviewers cannot distinguish structural change from behavioral change. Separate commits let each be reviewed on its own terms.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="TDD cycle as three commits">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Commit 1: failing test
git add tests/test_order.py
git commit -m "test: add failing test for order validation"

# Commit 2: minimum passing code
git add src/orders.py
git commit -m "feat: add order validation (min passing impl)"

# Commit 3: refactor
git add src/orders.py
git commit -m "refactor: extract validate_line_items() from validate_order()"
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="test-suite-speed">
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep the fast test suite under 10 minutes. Split into fast (unit, no I/O) and slow (integration, DB, external services) suites. Run fast on every push; slow on nightly or PR merge.</statement>
        <rationale>A suite that takes 30+ minutes kills the CI feedback loop. Developers push less frequently, decouple tests from code, and eventually skip them. The 10-minute rule forces the fast/slow split.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="mutation-testing">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run mutation testing (mutmut for Python, Stryker for JS/TS) on the critical path monthly. A mutation score below 70% means tests are not actually verifying behavior. Fix the tests, not the mutation score.</statement>
        <rationale>Coverage percentage measures which lines were executed; mutation score measures which behaviors were verified. A test that executes code without asserting its output counts as coverage but not as a test.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="xp-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Writing production code before the failing test exists.</description>
        <reason>Tests written after the fact verify the implementation, not the intended behavior. Pre-existing code biases test authors to test what was built rather than what was required. Invert the order unconditionally.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent adds interfaces, strategies, or factory classes without 2+ concrete implementations.</description>
        <reason>Speculative generality violates rule 4 (fewest elements). An interface with one implementation is a naming exercise that adds indirection without enabling extension. Reject any abstraction until the second concrete use case exists.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Combining refactor and feature changes in one commit.</description>
        <reason>Reviewers cannot distinguish structural change from behavioral change in a mixed commit. Refactors that inadvertently change behavior are invisible. Separate commits enable independent review of each concern.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Hero culture: one person owns a module and others cannot touch it.</description>
        <reason>Single-owner modules become bottlenecks and bus-factor risks. XP's collective ownership requires that any developer (or agent) can modify any code — enabled by comprehensive tests and standards.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM writes trivial getter/setter tests to hit coverage percentage instead of behavior tests.</description>
        <reason>Coverage percentage does not measure test quality; mutation score does. Trivial tests that call a getter and assert the returned value contribute 0 to mutation score and give false confidence.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent or human changes the CI test threshold or coding standards file without team review.</description>
        <reason>Standards files and CI thresholds are team-level decisions. An agent that lowers a coverage threshold to make a PR green is removing a quality gate, not fixing a quality problem.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sustainable pace violated by consistent late-night or weekend commits.</description>
        <reason>Tired developers write more bugs than they fix. Sprint velocity drops as bug rate rises and retrospectives become complaints sessions. Track commit timestamps; sustained off-hours patterns signal scope reduction is needed, not more hours.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Use Claude as the pair partner. A planner subagent breaks a story into a TDD task list (red tests, green code, refactor steps). An implementer subagent writes the failing test, then the minimum code to pass, then the refactor — three commits. A reviewer subagent enforces simplicity rules (no unused flexibility, DRY, smallest set of classes). A retrospective subagent reads the last N PRs and surfaces recurring smells (large diffs, skipped tests, no refactor commits).</p>
      <list>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — drives the TDD red→green→refactor loop with quality gates.</item>
        <item>tdd-pair (model: sonnet) — converts a story into a list of failing tests; never writes production code first.</item>
        <item>simplicity-reviewer (model: sonnet) — flags speculative generality, premature interfaces, and dead branches.</item>
        <item>retro-analyst (model: opus) — pulls last 2 weeks of git history + CI runs, returns themes for the iteration retro.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>pre-commit — Enforce coding standards on every commit (XP "Coding Standards" practice). `pip install pre-commit`</item>
        <item>pytest / vitest / jest / cargo test / go test — TDD red-green loop. Per language.</item>
        <item>mutmut / cosmic-ray (Py), stryker (JS/TS) — Mutation testing — proves tests actually test. `pip install mutmut`, `npm i -D @stryker-mutator/core`</item>
        <item>coverage.py / c8 / nyc — Coverage gate (≥ project bar, e.g. 80%). Per language.</item>
        <item>git rebase -i (informational) — Encourages small, focused commits. Bundled.</item>
        <item>commitlint — Enforce commit message style (consistency = standards). `npm i -D @commitlint/cli`</item>
        <item>tcr (test &amp;&amp; commit || revert) — Kent Beck's discipline-enforcer; punishes failed tests. https://github.com/murex/TCR</item>
        <item>Tuple / VS Code Live Share / Pop — Pair-programming over the network. https://tuple.app, etc.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Run the **fast** test suite on every save; full suite on every push; mutation tests nightly.</item>
        <item>Keep commits small enough that `git rebase -i` is mechanical; the XP rhythm is "test passes → commit".</item>
        <item>Pair sessions of 60-90 min with explicit "driver" rotation; longer sessions burn out, shorter waste warm-up.</item>
        <item>Pair on **risky** code (auth, payments, schema migrations); solo or AI-pair on boring CRUD.</item>
        <item>"Ten-minute rule": if your test suite takes more than 10 min, split into fast/slow and run fast on every push.</item>
        <item>Make the build's red status visible (Slack #ci-status, dashboard); fix-forward or revert within 10 minutes.</item>
        <item>Track velocity in a simple spreadsheet, not a tool — the moment teams "estimate to hit the velocity", the metric is dead.</item>
        <item>Refactor in a **separate** commit from feature changes — reviewers can read either lens cleanly.</item>
        <item>For solo + AI: Claude as pair is great for drivers' "what's the next test" prompt, but bad as the navigator (it doesn't push back enough). Have a human review every refactor commit.</item>
        <item>Keep a "do not pair on" list (admin tasks, exploratory spikes) so pairing doesn't become a tax.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs love to write production code first and tests second — invert with explicit "tests first, no implementation in this turn".</item>
        <item>LLMs over-test trivial getters; ask for **behavior** tests, not coverage tests.</item>
        <item>Refactor steps from agents often change behavior subtly (off-by-one, error-type swap). Always run full test suite between micro-refactors.</item>
        <item>Agents skip the "fewest elements" rule and add interfaces / strategies / factories preemptively. Reject any abstraction without 2+ concrete implementations.</item>
        <item>"Pair with AI" can degenerate into LLM-driven coding without review; institutionalize a human gate per PR.</item>
        <item>Agents can't enforce sustainable pace — but they can flag patterns: same human committing past 22:00 daily, weekend pushes, increasing test-skips. A retro subagent can surface this.</item>
        <item>TCR (test-commit-revert) discipline is hostile to LLMs: they revert often. Use TCR mode only when you trust the test suite stability.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: never let an agent unilaterally change the coding standards file or the CI test thresholds; those are team-level decisions.</item>
        <item>Mob/pair handover scripts: when using `mob` CLI with agent committers, ensure the agent identity is distinct from human committers (separate git author) so retros can analyze contribution sources.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/pre-commit-xp.yaml" purpose="pre-commit config enforcing ruff + pytest fast suite + no test skips"/>
    </templates>
